I believe that the commercial sector needs to take over humankind's expansion into space.  We WILL expand, if there's a profit to be made, and not taxpayers money to spend.  While Apollo was a great achievement, it did not establish us in space.  It was the cheap and fast way of getting to the Moon, with the assumption that you're never going back.<br>
<br>
NASA is talking about getting humans to Mars around 2015-2020.  This is further stimulated by Mars Odyssey's reports of vast underground deposits of water/ice (we're talking oceans).  I think that's a positive development, but I don't want another Apollo.  I say, if we go to Mars, let's go there to stay, or not go at all.  Provide a basis for future missions.  If NASA is going to stick with chemical, than at least it should attempt Zubrin's Mars Direct plan.  It provides a basis for the gradual construction of Martian cities, and eventually, the colonization of the planet. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/10/02 8:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=111.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Miners on the Moon by 2017?</span><hr size=1> It's good that someone out there is advocating extracting the material in space.  I'm a little doubtful though if mining the moon is the best way to get Helium 3.  It might be better to send probes to the outerplanets to gather helium 3 directly out of the atmospheres.  And since speed is of the essence in such operations, it might be a good driver of nuclear propulsion technology.  Just my two cents anyway.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=111.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=111.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.